 "span": {"begin": 1510, "end": 1522}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1956"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "EGFR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9958644509315491, "span": {"begin": 1524, "end": 1528}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1950"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "EGF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.99573814868927, "span": {"begin": 1533, "end": 1536}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ca2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989822506904602, "span": {"begin": 1571, "end": 1575}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ca2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990965127944946, "span": {"begin": 1707, "end": 1711}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Erk1/2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9962114095687866, "span": {"begin": 1716, "end": 1722}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:10746"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Mek1/2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9959086179733276, "span": {"begin": 1772, "end": 1778}}, {"id": ["mesh:C506614"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PD0325901", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991393089294434, "span": {"begin": 1784, "end": 1793}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ca2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993140697479248, "span": {"begin": 1854, "end": 1858}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Erk1/2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9974271655082703, "span": {"begin": 2002, "end": 2008}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ca2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9914984107017517, "span": {"begin": 2029, "end": 2033}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ca2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.998623251914978, "span": {"begin": 2118, "end": 2122}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Erk1/2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9924620985984802, "span": {"begin": 2172, "end": 2178}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ca2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992389678955078, "span": {"begin": 2291, "end": 2295}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Erk1/2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9963518381118774, "span": {"begin": 2306, "end": 2312}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Erk1/2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9975638389587402, "span": {"begin": 2407, "end": 2413}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "amputated tail", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5030484795570374, "span": {"begin": 2454, "end": 2468}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ca2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989175796508789, "span": {"begin": 2497, "end": 2501}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Erk1/2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.995821475982666, "span": {"begin": 2622, "end": 2628}}], "text": "We treated the astrocytes with a metal-mixture (MM) of arsenic, cadmium, and lead and observed that the MM triggered [Ca2+]i release&nbsp;(Rai and others 2010). The [Ca2+]i release reached its peak after 30 min of MM treatment. Similarly, MM triggered ROS generation, and the ROS generation reached its peak after 1 h of MM treatment. To investigate whether the [Ca2+]i release was ROS, ERK1/2, or JNK1/2 &ndash;dependent, we incubated the MM-treated astrocytes with an antioxidant (a-tocopherol, 200 lg/ml), PD98059 (10lM), or SP600125 (10lM). a-Tocopherol itself was nontoxic. We observed that PD98059 (10lM) or SP600125 (10lM) suppressed [Ca2+]i release, but a-tocopherol (200 lg/ml) did not. This suggested that [Ca2+]i release in MM-treated astrocytes was ERK1/2 and JNK1/2 dependent&nbsp;(Rai and others 2010).  Yael and Breitbart (2015) demonstrated for the first time that mouse sperm ERK1/2 is activated upon ZP addition, and that ERK1/2 mediates the elevation of intracellular Ca2+ in the sperm cell prior to the occurrence of the acrosome reaction. The fact that the acrosome reaction, induced by the Ca2+-ionophore A23187, was not inhibited by U0126 suggests that ERK1/2 mediates the acrosome reaction by activating Ca2+ transport into the cell. Direct determination of intracellular [Ca2+] revealed that Ca2+ influx induced by EGF or ZP was completely blocked by U0126. Thus, it has been established that the increase in ERK1/2 phosphorylation/activation in response to ZP or by activation of the EGF receptor (EGFR) by EGF, is a key event for intracellular Ca2+ elevation and the subsequent occurrence of the acrosome reaction&nbsp;(Jaldety et al., 2015).  To examine the relationship between Ca2+ and Erk1/2 signaling, Levin and Borodinsky (2022) inhibited Mek1/2 with PD0325901 and found that this prevents the injury-induced increase in Ca2+ activity in cells lateral to the axial musculature across the entire 800&nbsp;&micro;m-wide region measured. This suggests that injury-induced Erk1/2 activation recruits Ca2+ activity to promote regeneration of the larval tail. Consistent with recruitment of Ca2+ activity across a wide region of tail, activated Erk1/2 is also present in at least the posterior 800&nbsp;&micro;m of stump&nbsp;(Levin et al., 2022). However, unlike Ca2+ activity, Erk1/2 signaling at 20 mpa is activated in a gradient. This could mean that even the lowest level of Erk1/2 signal measured in 800&nbsp;&micro;m of amputated tail is sufficient to induce the Ca2+ response, or that a signal is propagated anteriorly from the cells adjacent to the amputation where injury induces high Erk1/2 activation&nbsp;(Levin et al., 2022).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:06:53 +0000 2026"}